&gt;Date: Thu, 05 Aug 2004 00:44:56 +0100
&gt;
&gt;Chad,
&gt;
&gt;Further to my previous email I was thinking about what sort and how many
&gt;test cases you would need in order to have a good attempt at evolving a
&gt;network to do a 3D vector cross product. Here&#39;s what I came up with...
&gt;
&gt;If you consider the origin of a (3D) cartesian coordinate system with
&gt;vectors coming out at all angles in all 3 dimensions you have a sort of
&gt;spikey sphere. You could then calculate the cross product of each of
&gt;these vectors with every other vector, and this should give you a good
&gt;enough set of examples for the neural net search to be able to
&gt;specialize and also to cover every possible set of vectors that we might
&gt;want to find a cross product for.
&gt;
&gt;By my thinking the smallest set of vectors that fits the above scheme
&gt;would have a set of vectors all seperated by 45 degrees, e.g. if we
&gt;think of one plane at a time, here is the x,y plane (z=0):
&gt;
&gt;                     View this in Courier New font if it looks a mess!
&gt;             y
&gt;          &#92;  |  /
&gt;           &#92; | /
&gt;            &#92;|/
&gt;       ------------ x
&gt;                              / | &#92;
&gt;                            /   |   &#92;
&gt;                          /     |     &#92;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Here we have 8 vectors, each seperated by 45 degrees. If we then take
&gt;this set of vectors and rotate it about the x axis by 45 degrees we get
&gt;another set of vectors - repeat this two more times and you end up with
&gt;26 vectors in all 3 dimensions that are evenly spread out and that form
&gt;a spikey sphere :)
&gt;
&gt;If we then compare each vector against itself and all of the others this
&gt;then makes 26*26=676 test cases. Remember that we should compare each
&gt;vector with itself so that we can be sure the network learns to generate
&gt;the zero vector when comparing parallel vectors.
&gt;
&gt;Of course it might be necessary to use an even larger set of vectors to
&gt;improve the accuracy of the evolved network - I don&#39;t know, but I think
&gt;the set described above is an absolute minimum.
&gt;
&gt;I hope that was clear enough and helps out a bit,
&gt;
&gt;Colin
